## Project info
- Product: Scopr — AI idea validation for non-technical people
- Tagline: "For people with lots of ideas but no idea where to start."
- Live at: tryscopr.com
- Stack: Next.js (app router), Tailwind CSS, Supabase, Claude API, Vercel

## Wordmark
Always render as: >_ Scopr where "Scop" is white and "r" is #4ADE80
The >_ sits in a small dark rounded square with a subtle border

## Pages already built
- app/page.tsx — landing page
- app/waitlist/page.js — waitlist with Supabase email capture
- app/auth/page.js — auth with email/password, Google OAuth, magic link

## Supabase tables
- waitlist — id, email, created_at
- profiles — id, username, display_name, email, created_at
- ideas — id, user_id, title, description, status (build/refine/refine), confidence_score, created_at

## Glass card effect
background: rgba(26, 27, 33, 0.8) with backdrop-filter: blur(8px)

## The three decisions (never call them verdicts)
- Build it — strong signals, high founder fit, high Q7 enthusiasm
- Needs refinement — addressable gaps, fixable in 2-4 weeks, Q7 must be high
- Revisit later — structural issues or low Q7. You cannot refine your way to passion.

## Security rules
- Always use RLS on every Supabase table
- Never expose service role key — anon key only in frontend
- All keys in .env.local — never commit to GitHub
- Auth protect all pages except /, /waitlist, /auth

## The product philosophy
Compete on confidence not features.
Every screen should ask: does this make the user feel more confident about their idea?